Non-obvious choices in task 8:

**Why directory-copy, not overlay / COW / ZFS snapshots.**
The alternatives are faster but platform-specific. Overlay fs is
Linux-only; APFS/BTRFS/ZFS snapshots need specific filesystems.
Directory copy works on every macOS and Linux setup we ship against
and has no hidden dependencies. For agent tool-call rollback the
workspace is typically small (source files, test output), so the
copy cost is acceptable. If real-world workspaces get big we can
add a fast-path per OS without changing the trait.

**Why snapshot doesn't stop the guest first.**
Semantics chosen to match the ADR's checkpoint model: the guest
keeps running while a snapshot is taken, so tool calls don't pay a
stop/restart tax for every checkpoint. The snapshot is a consistent
point-in-time copy for rollback purposes — if the guest races us
while we copy, the next snapshot will capture the post-race state.
Acceptable for rollback semantics; not acceptable for backup
semantics (which we're not claiming).

**Why restore doesn't re-launch the guest.**
Splitting "revert filesystem" from "restart guest" gives the caller
control. The task dispatcher (task 10) might want to restore FS only
(so the guest sees the reverted state on next read), or stop +
restore + relaunch (a full reset). Coupling them here would remove
that flexibility. The ADR's "drop the Store and re-instantiate"
flow is then: stop() → restore() → launch() — three explicit steps.

**Why SnapshotId is a String.**
Opaque-token pattern. Callers treat the id as a black box; internals
pick whatever scheme fits — UUID in our case, but something else if
we later back snapshots with content-addressed storage. Keeping the
type thin (newtype around String) means no serialization drama when
this eventually crosses an API boundary.

**Symlinks are skipped, not followed.**
A symlink inside a preopen could point anywhere on the host. If we
followed them, a malicious guest could trick us into copying arbitrary
host files into a snapshot — privilege escalation via copy. Skipping
them is the safe default. Guests that legitimately need symlinked
content inside their workspace can get it via additional preopens.

**Why `preopens` stored on RunningAgent and not re-derived from spec.**
ContainerSpec holds volumes (source, target, read_only). We compute
InstanceSpec.preopens from that at launch time. Storing it on the
RunningAgent means snapshot/restore don't have to re-run the
spec→instance_spec conversion and stay internally consistent with
what the guest actually got mounted.

**Why the unit test bypasses the guest and mutates the workspace
directly.**
The point of the test is the snapshot/restore plumbing, not
demonstrating that a real guest can mutate files (which we already
know WASI fd_write does). Using host-side file IO to simulate guest
mutations means the test is fast, hermetic, and not coupled to
whatever WAT I author. The CLI smoke does the same — mutates the
workspace from the outside to simulate a tool call.

**Why restore removes the existing dir before copying back (instead
of overlay-merging).**
If restore merged (kept existing files + added snapshot files on top)
then a guest that *created* a file post-snapshot would keep it after
restore — the exact failure mode rollback is supposed to prevent.
Clearing first guarantees the workspace matches the snapshot exactly.
